## Step 6: Culture and Guardrails (So SREs Don’t Revolt)

AIOps isn’t “AI replaces ops”; it’s “AI supports ops.” Adoption fails if teams feel it’s being done *to* them instead of *with* them. [web:302][web:312][web:310][web:287][web:289]

Success factors:

- Involve the team:
  - SREs/DevOps help choose use cases, tune rules, and decide what to automate. [web:306][web:312][web:309]
- Transparency:
  - Make AIOps decisions and suggestions visible (dashboards, chat), not black‑box. [web:304][web:306][web:309]
- Training:
  - Teach people what the models do and don’t do; emphasise they’re fallible helpers. [web:301][web:312][web:282]
- Clear limits:
  - Document what is allowed to auto‑remediate and what always needs human approval. [web:302][web:304][web:306][web:312]

The aim is to reduce **alert fatigue and manual grind**, not to remove engineers from the loop for meaningful incidents. [web:302][web:295][web:287][web:281]

